{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644935"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:11:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:11:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18073"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18073"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74955"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10787"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18073"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60461"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5735"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25959"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74955"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe concept of personhood is central to many debates in medical ethics. Various philosophical frameworks have been proposed to define what constitutes a person, as distinct from simply being biologically human.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is considered a necessary characteristic for personhood according to most philosophical frameworks?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Physical human form","Ability to feel pain","Biological viability","Self-awareness and rationality","Genetic human DNA"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eself-awareness and rationality\u003C/strong\u003E. Most philosophical frameworks consider these cognitive capabilities as essential components of personhood, along with consciousness and moral agency. This distinguishes the concept of personhood from purely biological human life.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysical human form\u003C/strong\u003E - External physical appearance does not establish personhood, as philosophical arguments demonstrate that non-human entities may possess person-like qualities.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbility to feel pain\u003C/strong\u003E - While pain perception indicates sentience, this characteristic alone is insufficient for personhood, as many non-human animals can experience pain.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiological viability\u003C/strong\u003E - The capacity to maintain independent biological functions does not establish personhood, as evidenced by patients in persistent vegetative states.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic human DNA\u003C/strong\u003E - The presence of human genetic material is insufficient to confer personhood, as individual human cells contain DNA but are not considered persons.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding personhood is crucial for medical ethics as it influences decisions about beginning and end of life care, research ethics, and patient autonomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Personhood requires key characteristics including consciousness, rationality, self-awareness, and moral agency.","The philosophical concept of personhood is distinct from biological human life.","Personhood status has important implications for medical ethics and decision-making."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60461"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18073"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60461"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T12:40:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T12:41:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10787"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74955"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5631"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83